    "UNITS": {
        "CSSPostAmines": {
            "Unit Description": "Post-combustion carbon capture with amines is a widely used method to reduce `CO_{2}` emissions from power plants and industrial processes. The operating principle involves passing the flue gas through an absorber where the `CO_{2}` is captured by contacting it with a chemical solvent, typically an amine at below 60°C. The `CO_{2}`-rich solvent, also known as rich amine, is then pumped to a desorber or stripper. In the desorber, heat is supplied to the rich amine solution, typically through low pressure steam (above 120°C) in the reboiler, which helps releasing the `CO_{2}` out from the solvent. The released `CO_{2}` is separated, while the regenerated or lean amine solution, which is now depleted of `CO_{2}`, is recycled back to the absorber to capture more `CO_{2}` from the flue gas. The lean amine solution, which is recycled back to the absorber, usually has a concentration of amine not higher than 45% wt and a `CO_{2}` concentration (i.e. amine loading) not higher than 0.3 kmol `CO_{2}` per kmol of amine to avoid corrosion problems.",
            "Unit Info": {
